docs.abstract: Here are some of the archaic rules and procedures that make an impeachment trial so unusual.
docs.snippet: Here are some of the archaic rules and procedures that make an impeachment trial so unusual.
docs.lead_paragraph: Wednesday begins a fast-moving series of customs that formally initiate an impeachment trial. My colleague Nick Fandos wrote a helpful preview of those procedures. Here’s a look at some of what’s to come in the next week.

headline.main: Impeachment Briefing: Quirks of the Trial

docs.abstract: The intelligence agency alerted Microsoft to a vulnerability in Windows. Typically, it would keep quiet and exploit the flaw.
docs.snippet: The intelligence agency alerted Microsoft to a vulnerability in Windows. Typically, it would keep quiet and exploit the flaw.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The National Security Agency has taken a significant step toward protecting the world’s computer systems, announcing Tuesday that it alerted Microsoft to a vulnerability in its Windows operating system rather than following the agency’s typical approach of keeping quiet and exploiting the flaw to develop cyberweapons.

headline.main: N.S.A. Takes Step Toward Protecting World’s Computers, Not Just Hacking Them
headline.print_headline: Seeing Digital Flaw, N.S.A. Decides to Warn, Not Snoop

byline.original: By Julian E. Barnes and David E. Sanger

docs.abstract: Chief Justice John Roberts’s role at an impeachment trial may be mostly ceremonial, but signs of partisanship could damage the Supreme Court.
docs.snippet: Chief Justice John Roberts’s role at an impeachment trial may be mostly ceremonial, but signs of partisanship could damage the Supreme Court.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Chief Justice John G. Roberts Jr. walks out of his chambers at the Supreme Court, crosses First Street and enters the Capitol to preside over President Trump’s impeachment trial, he will leave behind an institution that prides itself on reason and decorum and enter one marked by partisan warfare.

headline.main: Trump’s Impeachment Trial a Perilous Duty for Chief Justice
headline.print_headline: Roberts’s Role Is Ceremonial And Perilous

docs.abstract: The Senate Republican leader proposed impeachment trial rules that push the 1999 precedent toward President Trump’s preferences.
docs.snippet: The Senate Republican leader proposed impeachment trial rules that push the 1999 precedent toward President Trump’s preferences.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For weeks, Senator Mitch McConnell sought to deflect charges that he was trying to stack the deck in favor of President Trump in his impeachment trial by repeating that he was merely replicating the Senate’s only modern precedent: the 1999 trial of President Bill Clinton.

headline.main: McConnell Impeachment Rules Modify Clinton Precedent
headline.print_headline: Procedures That Modify A Precedent From 1999

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Mitch McConnell, the majority leader, unveiled ground rules on Monday for President Trump’s impeachment trial that would attempt to speed the proceeding along and refuse to admit the evidence against the president unearthed by the House without a separate vote.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As President Trump’s impeachment trial opens, his lawyers have increasingly emphasized a striking argument: Even if he did abuse his powers in an attempt to bully Ukraine into interfering in the 2020 election on his behalf, it would not matter because the House never accused him of committing an ordinary crime.
